Again: 21 divided by 9 quotes 2, remainder 3; wherefore, 3765 divided by 9 quotes
                    4∣18, remainders; for the reason given. Hence we may collect the following rules
                    for practice:

Method 2. Divide the rate into aliquot parts of a pound;
                    calculate the values corresponding to these, as directed in Case I., and add
                    them.

Sometimes part of the value is more readily obtained from a part already found;
                    and sometimes it is easiest to calculate at a higher rate, and subtract the
                    value at the difference.

The numerators of fractions that have the same denominator signify like parts;
                    and the reason for adding them is equally obvious as that for adding shillings
                    or any other inferior denomination.

In order to add these vulgar fractions, we reduce them to a common denominator;
                    and for that purpose we multiply both terms of the former by 99, which gives
                    f⅝⅛⅛⅞5 then we add the numerators.
